[h1]Associative Arrays[/h1]

While many programming languages support arrays with named indexes (text instead of numbers), called [b]associative arrays[/b],[b] [/b]JavaScript [b]does not[/b].
However, you still can use the named array syntax, which will produce an object.
[b]For example:[/b]
[code format="js" codeId="700"]var person = []; //empty array
person["name"] = "John";
person["age"] = 46;
document.write(person["age"]);
//Outputs "46"[/code]Now, person is treated as an object, instead of being an array.
The named indexes "name" and "age" become properties of the person object.
[note]As the person array is treated as an object, the standard array methods and properties will produce incorrect results. For example, [b]person.length[/b] will return 0.[/note]
